Some of the many, specific safety features to prevent chemical accidents include:
-Computer controlled safety systems on the phosphorous trichloride storage and transfer systems to ensure that any deviations from the intended operating conditions are immediately identified and corrected;
-Safety procedures that reduce the potential for human error which could lead to a storage tank overfill;
-Secondary containment dikes around storage tanks and tank truck unloading areas to contain a spill;
-Building enclosures around phosphorous trichloride tank truck unloading and storage equipment to contain a leak;
-Both the unloading and storage building enclosures are equipped with a water deluge system that can be readily connected to a water supply to mitigate the release of vapors from the building;
-Phosphorous trichloride liquid is transferred through a double-walled or pipe-within-a-pipe system to prevent leaks to the atmosphere;
-Phosphorous trichloride piping system is equipment with electronic sensors to detect a leak within inner piping system;
-General area gas sensors are located within both the storage and unloading buildings to detect and warn of a release of phosphorous trichloride during the transfer or storage; 
-Chemical Operators are present during the unloading and transfer of phosphorus trichloride; 
-Both the unloading and storage building are under continuous video surveillance with the monitors being located in within two separate control rooms (i.e., 181 and 183 Control Rms);
-Extensive safety information about the processes is reviewed with employees through our company's H

azard Communication Program (HAZCOM) and other Standard Operating Procedures relating to the processes;
-Written operating procedures that include emergency response actions; 
-Comprehensive employee and contractor training programs to promote consistent safe work-practices; 
-Mechanical Integrity/Maintenance programs to ensure ongoing equipment reliability - includes equipment testing and inspection;
-Performance of scheduled Process Hazard Analysis (PHA's) to assess potential causes and consequences of fires, explosions, releases of toxic or flammable chemicals and major spills of hazardous chemicals, and focus on equipment, instrumentation, utilities, human actions , and external factors that might impact the process;
-Establishment of  Management of Change (MOC) procedure to review proposed plant modifications before they are implemented to assess potential hazards;  
-Safety pre-qualification for all contractors; 
-Establishment of Process Startup Safety Review (PSSR) program to assess potential hazards associated with the processes prior to startup; and, 
-Safety-permit procedures that control hazards during special operations such as welding and other maintenance activities. 

6.0  FIVE YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY

Over the long term, the Morgantown, WV site has had a positive accident prevention record that demonstrates its commitment to public and worker safety.  Even minor incidents are investigated to identify what went wrong and to learn how to prevent future occurrences.  EPA requires that all incidents involving RMP-regulated chemicals that resulted in any off-site impact or  on-site impacts as defined by the RMP rules are reported in this document.  

